{"parentUuid":"9ea949cc-ba9f-46f4-af6e-f8f175fab83b","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a2cceb1c12f4a6bcd","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01YXy1fZQH8je2MuHeAtC5La","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01EpoLzEWGa9azcaGNQsRAeY","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"contextual bandit LinUCB LLM routing reasoning effort think mode 2025"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1003,"cache_creation_input_tokens":11809,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":11809,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":{"cache_miss_reason":{"type":"tools_changed","cache_missed_input_tokens":7751}}},"requestId":"req_011CcFx72njzWmnynrK41xVH","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"dde1607f-8498-4a82-878c-7d1dda6f9e9f","timestamp":"2026-06-21T06:43:02.566Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"06335594-126c-4a7d-9c3f-f27dad6c8cf7","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"896d0f12-96e2-42a4-8fdf-b1fab5546f55","agentId":"a2cceb1c12f4a6bcd","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01YD7CGsad2GMBLhzSgaWz5j","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"MLX-LM LoRA fine-tuning Apple Silicon 16GB memory requirements qwen 8B\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Fine-Tuning on Mac: LoRA & QLoRA with MLX | InsiderLLM\",\"url\":\"https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-mac-lora-mlx/\"},{\"title\":\"Train Your Own LLM on MacBook: A Fine-tuning Guide with MLX | by Dushyant Mahajan | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@dummahajan/train-your-own-llm-on-macbook-a-15-minute-guide-with-mlx-6c6ed9ad036a\"},{\"title\":\"MLX Apple Silicon AI Dev Stack: Fine-Tune LLMs on Mac\",\"url\":\"https://www.buildmvpfast.com/blog/mlx-apple-silicon-ai-development-mac-fine-tune-llm-2026\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - ARahim3/mlx-tune: Fine-tune LLMs on your Mac with Apple Silicon. SFT, DPO, GRPO, Vision, TTS, STT, Embedding, and OCR fine-tuning — natively on MLX. Unsloth-compatible API.\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/ARahim3/mlx-tune\"},{\"title\":\"Fine-Tuning LLMs with LoRA and MLX-LM | by Joana Levtcheva | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@levchevajoana/fine-tuning-llms-with-lora-and-mlx-lm-c0b143642deb\"},{\"title\":\"Fine-Tuning LLMs Locally Using MLX LM\",\"url\":\"https://dzone.com/articles/fine-tuning-llms-locally-using-mlx-lm-guide\"},{\"title\":\"Best LLM for Mac 2026: Picks for M1/M2/M3/M4 by RAM Tier | Will It Run AI Blog\",\"url\":\"https://willitrunai.com/blog/best-llm-for-mac-apple-silicon-2026\"},{\"title\":\"Run and Fine-Tune LLMs on Mac with MLX-LM 2026 | Markaicode\",\"url\":\"https://markaicode.com/run-fine-tune-llms-mac-mlx-lm/\"},{\"title\":\"How to Fine-Tune a Small LLM on a Laptop: Hardware Guide\",\"url\":\"https://www.laptophub.net/how-to-fine-tune-small-llm-on-laptop/\"},{\"title\":\"Qwen 3.5 on Apple Silicon MLX (2026) — Memory Usage, Tokens/sec & Setup Guide | Will It Run AI Blog\",\"url\":\"https://willitrunai.com/blog/qwen-3-5-mlx-apple-silicon-guide\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about MLX-LM LoRA fine-tuning on Apple Silicon with 16GB memory for Qwen 8B models:\n\n## Memory Requirements & Feasibility\n\nQLoRA on a 16GB MacBook fine-tunes an 8B model in about an hour. This is directly applicable to Qwen 8B models, as supported architectures include Qwen2 (and the newer Qwen versions).\n\nThe guide covers MLX-LM fine-tuning tested on M2/M3 with 16GB RAM. Additionally, a 16GB M2 Pro chip was successfully used to fine-tune multiple smaller LLMs with MLX and LoRA, including 8B models.\n\n## Practical Configuration for 16GB Macs\n\nFor 8B models on 16GB Apple Silicon:\n- Start with 8 LoRA layers for quick experiments, increase to 16–32 for production adapters on 16GB+ machines.\n- On a 16GB M2 MacBook Pro, you can fine-tune a LoRA adapter on a custom dataset in under 30 minutes (for 7B models; 8B will be similar).\n\n## Memory Optimization Strategy\n\nWhen you pass a 4-bit quantized model with --train, MLX-LM automatically does QLoRA: the base stays quantized, only the LoRA adapter weights are full precision. This is key for fitting 8B models on 16GB machines.\n\n## Dataset Size\n\nGive it a JSONL file with 200-500 examples as a starting point for efficient fine-tuning on consumer hardware like 16GB Macs.\n\nIn summary, **16GB of unified memory is sufficient for QLoRA fine-tuning of Qwen 8B models** with MLX-LM, though you'll want to use quantized base models and moderate LoRA layer counts.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"c00f7ce8-8c31-4681-9115-788a70560933","timestamp":"2026-06-21T06:43:10.334Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"MLX-LM LoRA fine-tuning Apple Silicon 16GB memory requirements qwen 8B","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01MuqHa7xt68ZxiTJLu8aL2e","content":[{"title":"Fine-Tuning on Mac: LoRA & QLoRA with MLX | InsiderLLM","url":"https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-mac-lora-mlx/"},{"title":"Train Your Own LLM on MacBook: A Fine-tuning Guide with MLX | by Dushyant Mahajan | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@dummahajan/train-your-own-llm-on-macbook-a-15-minute-guide-with-mlx-6c6ed9ad036a"},{"title":"MLX Apple Silicon AI Dev Stack: Fine-Tune LLMs on Mac","url":"https://www.buildmvpfast.com/blog/mlx-apple-silicon-ai-development-mac-fine-tune-llm-2026"},{"title":"GitHub - ARahim3/mlx-tune: Fine-tune LLMs on your Mac with Apple Silicon. SFT, DPO, GRPO, Vision, TTS, STT, Embedding, and OCR fine-tuning — natively on MLX. Unsloth-compatible API.","url":"https://github.com/ARahim3/mlx-tune"},{"title":"Fine-Tuning LLMs with LoRA and MLX-LM | by Joana Levtcheva | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@levchevajoana/fine-tuning-llms-with-lora-and-mlx-lm-c0b143642deb"},{"title":"Fine-Tuning LLMs Locally Using MLX LM","url":"https://dzone.com/articles/fine-tuning-llms-locally-using-mlx-lm-guide"},{"title":"Best LLM for Mac 2026: Picks for M1/M2/M3/M4 by RAM Tier | Will It Run AI Blog","url":"https://willitrunai.com/blog/best-llm-for-mac-apple-silicon-2026"},{"title":"Run and Fine-Tune LLMs on Mac with MLX-LM 2026 | Markaicode","url":"https://markaicode.com/run-fine-tune-llms-mac-mlx-lm/"},{"title":"How to Fine-Tune a Small LLM on a Laptop: Hardware Guide","url":"https://www.laptophub.net/how-to-fine-tune-small-llm-on-laptop/"},{"title":"Qwen 3.5 on Apple Silicon MLX (2026) — Memory Usage, Tokens/sec & Setup Guide | Will It Run AI Blog","url":"https://willitrunai.com/blog/qwen-3-5-mlx-apple-silicon-guide"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about MLX-LM LoRA fine-tuning on Apple Silicon with 16GB memory for Qwen 8B models:\n\n## Memory Requirements & Feasibility\n\nQLoRA on a 16GB MacBook fine-tunes an 8B model in about an hour. This is directly applicable to Qwen 8B models, as supported architectures include Qwen2 (and the newer Qwen versions).\n\nThe guide covers MLX-LM fine-tuning tested on M2/M3 with 16GB RAM. Additionally, a 16GB M2 Pro chip was successfully used to fine-tune multiple smaller LLMs with MLX and LoRA, including 8B models.\n\n## Practical Configuration for 16GB Macs\n\nFor 8B models on 16GB Apple Silicon:\n- Start with 8 LoRA layers for quick experiments, increase to 16–32 for production adapters on 16GB+ machines.\n- On a 16GB M2 MacBook Pro, you can fine-tune a LoRA adapter on a custom dataset in under 30 minutes (for 7B models; 8B will be similar).\n\n## Memory Optimization Strategy\n\nWhen you pass a 4-bit quantized model with --train, MLX-LM automatically does QLoRA: the base stays quantized, only the LoRA adapter weights are full precision. This is key for fitting 8B models on 16GB machines.\n\n## Dataset Size\n\nGive it a JSONL file with 200-500 examples as a starting point for efficient fine-tuning on consumer hardware like 16GB Macs.\n\nIn summary, **16GB of unified memory is sufficient for QLoRA fine-tuning of Qwen 8B models** with MLX-LM, though you'll want to use quantized base models and moderate LoRA layer counts."],"durationSeconds":8.580556125000118,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"06335594-126c-4a7d-9c3f-f27dad6c8cf7","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"9ea949cc-ba9f-46f4-af6e-f8f175fab83b","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"896d0f12-96e2-42a4-8fdf-b1fab5546f55","agentId":"a2cceb1c12f4a6bcd","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QezYMGhY18wbiFbDFpHWbw","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"QLoRA memory math 7B 8B model fine-tuning VRAM requirements 2024\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Fine-Tuning LLMs on Consumer Hardware: LoRA and QLoRA Guide | InsiderLLM\",\"url\":\"https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-local-lora-qlora/\"},{\"title\":\"LoRA vs Full Fine-Tuning Memory Cost: VRAM Math for... | Lyceum Technology\",\"url\":\"https://lyceum.technology/magazine/lora-vs-full-fine-tuning-memory-cost/\"},{\"title\":\"LLM Fine-Tuning Hardware Requirements: VRAM, GPU\",\"url\":\"https://llmhardware.io/guides/llm-fine-tuning-hardware-requirements\"},{\"title\":\"Fine-Tuning Infrastructure: LoRA, QLoRA, and PEFT at Scale | Introl Blog\",\"url\":\"https://introl.com/blog/fine-tuning-infrastructure-lora-qlora-peft-scale-guide-2025\"},{\"title\":\"How much VRAM do I need for LLM model fine-tuning?\",\"url\":\"https://modal.com/blog/how-much-vram-need-fine-tuning\"},{\"title\":\"How can I fine-tune large language models on a budget using LoRA and QLoRA on cloud GPUs?\",\"url\":\"https://www.runpod.io/articles/guides/how-to-fine-tune-large-language-models-on-a-budget\"},{\"title\":\"LLaMA-XR: A Novel Framework for Radiology Report Generation using LLaMA and QLoRA Fine Tuning\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.03178\"},{\"title\":\"Guide to GPU Requirements for Running AI Models\",\"url\":\"https://www.bacloud.com/en/blog/163/guide-to-gpu-requirements-for-running-ai-models.html\"},{\"title\":\"Fine-tuning LLaMA-7B on ~12GB VRAM with QLoRA, 4-bit quantization · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://gist.github.com/Birch-san/57878c4a27cf34f57d3e861865a7d0a2\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about QLoRA memory requirements for 7B and 8B model fine-tuning:\n\n## VRAM Requirements for QLoRA Fine-Tuning\n\n**7B Models:**\nQLoRA requires 12 GB VRAM for 7B models. In practice, an RTX 3060 12GB can train a 7B model with QLoRA, and you can fine-tune a 7B model on an RTX 3060 12GB in a few hours.\n\n**8B Models:**\nQLoRA combined with paged optimizers can push the VRAM requirement for an 8B model down to 6GB, making it viable for consumer hardware. Alternatively, LoRA (without quantization) drops the 8B model VRAM requirement from 69GB to 16GB by only tracking gradients and optimizer states for millions of adapter parameters instead of billions of base parameters.\n\n## Memory Math Explanation\n\nQLoRA loads the base model at 4-bit quantization first, then trains LoRA adapters on top, cutting VRAM requirements by roughly half compared to standard LoRA with minimal quality loss. 4-bit quantization compresses base model weights to NormalFloat (NF4) format, reducing memory by 75% versus 16-bit, and double quantization quantizes the quantization constants themselves, saving additional memory.\n\nFor comparison, full fine-tuning of a 7-billion parameter model requires 100-120GB VRAM, but QLoRA enables the same fine-tuning on a $1,500 RTX 4090.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"6430ad8c-a65e-4c32-aee5-e2edb0f4281c","timestamp":"2026-06-21T06:43:10.796Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"QLoRA memory math 7B 8B model fine-tuning VRAM requirements 2024","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_0134PixJC3jqpssbv49M8BBv","content":[{"title":"Fine-Tuning LLMs on Consumer Hardware: LoRA and QLoRA Guide | InsiderLLM","url":"https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-local-lora-qlora/"},{"title":"LoRA vs Full Fine-Tuning Memory Cost: VRAM Math for... | Lyceum Technology","url":"https://lyceum.technology/magazine/lora-vs-full-fine-tuning-memory-cost/"},{"title":"LLM Fine-Tuning Hardware Requirements: VRAM, GPU","url":"https://llmhardware.io/guides/llm-fine-tuning-hardware-requirements"},{"title":"Fine-Tuning Infrastructure: LoRA, QLoRA, and PEFT at Scale | Introl Blog","url":"https://introl.com/blog/fine-tuning-infrastructure-lora-qlora-peft-scale-guide-2025"},{"title":"How much VRAM do I need for LLM model fine-tuning?","url":"https://modal.com/blog/how-much-vram-need-fine-tuning"},{"title":"How can I fine-tune large language models on a budget using LoRA and QLoRA on cloud GPUs?","url":"https://www.runpod.io/articles/guides/how-to-fine-tune-large-language-models-on-a-budget"},{"title":"LLaMA-XR: A Novel Framework for Radiology Report Generation using LLaMA and QLoRA Fine Tuning","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.03178"},{"title":"Guide to GPU Requirements for Running AI Models","url":"https://www.bacloud.com/en/blog/163/guide-to-gpu-requirements-for-running-ai-models.html"},{"title":"Fine-tuning LLaMA-7B on ~12GB VRAM with QLoRA, 4-bit quantization · GitHub","url":"https://gist.github.com/Birch-san/57878c4a27cf34f57d3e861865a7d0a2"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about QLoRA memory requirements for 7B and 8B model fine-tuning:\n\n## VRAM Requirements for QLoRA Fine-Tuning\n\n**7B Models:**\nQLoRA requires 12 GB VRAM for 7B models. In practice, an RTX 3060 12GB can train a 7B model with QLoRA, and you can fine-tune a 7B model on an RTX 3060 12GB in a few hours.\n\n**8B Models:**\nQLoRA combined with paged optimizers can push the VRAM requirement for an 8B model down to 6GB, making it viable for consumer hardware. Alternatively, LoRA (without quantization) drops the 8B model VRAM requirement from 69GB to 16GB by only tracking gradients and optimizer states for millions of adapter parameters instead of billions of base parameters.\n\n## Memory Math Explanation\n\nQLoRA loads the base model at 4-bit quantization first, then trains LoRA adapters on top, cutting VRAM requirements by roughly half compared to standard LoRA with minimal quality loss. 4-bit quantization compresses base model weights to NormalFloat (NF4) format, reducing memory by 75% versus 16-bit, and double quantization quantizes the quantization constants themselves, saving additional memory.\n\nFor comparison, full fine-tuning of a 7-billion parameter model requires 100-120GB VRAM, but QLoRA enables the same fine-tuning on a $1,500 RTX 4090."],"durationSeconds":8.150759666999802,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"9ea949cc-ba9f-46f4-af6e-f8f175fab83b","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"dde1607f-8498-4a82-878c-7d1dda6f9e9f","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"896d0f12-96e2-42a4-8fdf-b1fab5546f55","agentId":"a2cceb1c12f4a6bcd","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01EpoLzEWGa9azcaGNQsRAeY","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"contextual bandit LinUCB LLM routing reasoning effort think mode 2025\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"[2506.17670] Online Multi-LLM Selection via Contextual Bandits under Unstructured Context Evolution\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.17670\"},{\"title\":\"Preprint. Under Review. LEARNING TO ROUTE LLMS FROM BANDIT FEED-\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.07429\"},{\"title\":\"Learning to Route LLMs from Bandit Feedback: One Policy, Many Trade-offs\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2510.07429v1\"},{\"title\":\"Dynamic Model Routing and Cascading for Efficient LLM Inference: A Survey\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.04445\"},{\"title\":\"Online Multi-LLM Selection via Contextual Bandits Under Unstructured Context Evolution | Request PDF\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/402629939_Online_Multi-LLM_Selection_via_Contextual_Bandits_Under_Unstructured_Context_Evolution\"},{\"title\":\"Online Multi-LLM Selection via Contextual Bandits under ...\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.17670\"},{\"title\":\"Online Multi-LLM Selection via Contextual Bandits\",\"url\":\"https://ojs.aaai.org/index.php/AAAI/article/download/39672/43633\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found on contextual bandit approaches for LLM routing:\n\n## Recent Research on Contextual Bandits for LLM Routing (2025)\n\nContextual bandit methods are being used to achieve real-time, adaptive LLM selection that outperforms existing routing strategies in both accuracy and cost-efficiency.\n\n### Key Approaches:\n\n**LinUCB-Based Methods:**\nMetaLLM employs LinUCB to select an LLM by learning a policy that predicts a reward (balancing accuracy and cost) based on query embeddings. Additionally, PILOT (Preference-prior Informed LinUCB for Adaptive Routing) extends contextual bandits by integrating offline human preference data with online evaluative feedback, building on the LinUCB algorithm widely used in recommender systems.\n\n**Multi-Step LLM Selection:**\nRecent work introduces the first contextual bandit framework for multi-step LLM selection under unstructured context evolution, proposing a Greedy LinUCB algorithm for per-step LLM selection and establishing a sublinear regret bound with respect to myopic regret.\n\n**Policy Gradient Approaches:**\nMixLLM employs a contextual bandit framework with policy gradient methods to optimize query-LLM assignments, and during online deployment updates its routing policy using binary user feedback through a dynamic feedback score mechanism.\n\n### Bandit Algorithms Compared:\nClassic bandit algorithms being used include LinUCB, Thompson Sampling, and ϵ-greedy for LLM routing decisions.\n\nRegarding \"reasoning effort\" and \"think mode,\" the search results don't contain specific information connecting these concepts to the bandit-based routing framework.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"dc82e639-c57a-4be0-93f9-3d527ab06614","timestamp":"2026-06-21T06:43:15.013Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"contextual bandit LinUCB LLM routing reasoning effort think mode 2025","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01VsRZHCvNWnUejFZNMjVW3v","content":[{"title":"[2506.17670] Online Multi-LLM Selection via Contextual Bandits under Unstructured Context Evolution","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.17670"},{"title":"Preprint. Under Review. LEARNING TO ROUTE LLMS FROM BANDIT FEED-","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.07429"},{"title":"Learning to Route LLMs from Bandit Feedback: One Policy, Many Trade-offs","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2510.07429v1"},{"title":"Dynamic Model Routing and Cascading for Efficient LLM Inference: A Survey","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.04445"},{"title":"Online Multi-LLM Selection via Contextual Bandits Under Unstructured Context Evolution | Request PDF","url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/402629939_Online_Multi-LLM_Selection_via_Contextual_Bandits_Under_Unstructured_Context_Evolution"},{"title":"Online Multi-LLM Selection via Contextual Bandits under ...","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.17670"},{"title":"Online Multi-LLM Selection via Contextual Bandits","url":"https://ojs.aaai.org/index.php/AAAI/article/download/39672/43633"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found on contextual bandit approaches for LLM routing:\n\n## Recent Research on Contextual Bandits for LLM Routing (2025)\n\nContextual bandit methods are being used to achieve real-time, adaptive LLM selection that outperforms existing routing strategies in both accuracy and cost-efficiency.\n\n### Key Approaches:\n\n**LinUCB-Based Methods:**\nMetaLLM employs LinUCB to select an LLM by learning a policy that predicts a reward (balancing accuracy and cost) based on query embeddings. Additionally, PILOT (Preference-prior Informed LinUCB for Adaptive Routing) extends contextual bandits by integrating offline human preference data with online evaluative feedback, building on the LinUCB algorithm widely used in recommender systems.\n\n**Multi-Step LLM Selection:**\nRecent work introduces the first contextual bandit framework for multi-step LLM selection under unstructured context evolution, proposing a Greedy LinUCB algorithm for per-step LLM selection and establishing a sublinear regret bound with respect to myopic regret.\n\n**Policy Gradient Approaches:**\nMixLLM employs a contextual bandit framework with policy gradient methods to optimize query-LLM assignments, and during online deployment updates its routing policy using binary user feedback through a dynamic feedback score mechanism.\n\n### Bandit Algorithms Compared:\nClassic bandit algorithms being used include LinUCB, Thompson Sampling, and ϵ-greedy for LLM routing decisions.\n\nRegarding \"reasoning effort\" and \"think mode,\" the search results don't contain specific information connecting these concepts to the bandit-based routing framework."],"durationSeconds":12.267377000000328,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"dde1607f-8498-4a82-878c-7d1dda6f9e9f","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
