{"parentUuid":"28b18412-e62c-4bd0-b77f-321ee80ae543","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a2cceb1c12f4a6bcd","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01PRPdmmTLZSmMruxGCXcgkR","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_0189SJXCmL3RepmVDmHJmLiC","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-mac-lora-mlx/","prompt":"Extract concrete memory numbers, timing, and quality for LoRA/QLoRA fine-tuning on 16GB Apple Silicon Macs for 7B/8B models. What model sizes fit? How long does training take? Failure modes mentioned?"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5384,"cache_read_input_tokens":11809,"output_tokens":465,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5384},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":465,"cache_read_input_tokens":11809,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5384,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5384,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFx8FxH6JhzHmECrAGF2","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"cba4a65c-16b3-4176-a771-a6ef7901beb4","timestamp":"2026-06-21T06:43:22.570Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"47825c32-65ed-4c07-88e1-2d74d67b1643","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"32c7be0a-d03a-4f99-b63a-5bc0ac6e352a","agentId":"a2cceb1c12f4a6bcd","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CAnvH2b9LKAtUppFhw5rKr","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"adaptive reasoning effort routing reasoning models thinking budget 2025 2026 router accuracy latency\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Adaptive Model and Strategy Routing for Cost-Efficient LLM Services | Proceedings of the ACM Web Conference 2026\",\"url\":\"https://dl.acm.org/doi/abs/10.1145/3774904.3792556\"},{\"title\":\"Reasoning-Effort Budgeting: When Thinking Tokens Become a Finance Line Item - TianPan.co\",\"url\":\"https://tianpan.co/blog/2026-04-27-reasoning-effort-budgeting-thinking-token-line-item\"},{\"title\":\"ARES: Adaptive Reasoning Effort Selection for Efficient LLM Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.07915\"},{\"title\":\"From Efficiency to Adaptivity: A Deeper Look at Adaptive Reasoning in Large Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.10788v2\"},{\"title\":\"SAT: Balancing Reasoning Accuracy and Efficiency with Stepwise Adaptive Thinking\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2604.07922v1\"},{\"title\":\"From Efficiency to Adaptivity: A Deeper Look at Adaptive Reasoning in Large Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2511.10788\"},{\"title\":\"Energy-Efficient Scaling of LLM Reasoning via Reinforced ...\",\"url\":\"https://fi.ee.tsinghua.edu.cn/public/publications/08487c64-ff50-11f0-b382-2aaffa21d846.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Towards Concise and Adaptive Thinking in Large Reasoning Models: A Survey\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2507.09662\"}]\n\nI found several relevant research papers and articles on adaptive reasoning effort routing and related concepts from 2025-2026. Here are the key findings:\n\n## Adaptive Reasoning Effort Routing\n\nRTR (a routing system) dynamically assigns the most appropriate model pair during inference, enabling adaptive and cost-efficient reasoning tailored to query difficulty and budget scenarios.\n\n## Router Approaches and Models\n\nRouteLLM learns a lightweight router from preference data to dispatch easy inputs to cheaper small models and difficult ones to larger models, reducing total compute without degrading accuracy.\n\nSelfBudgeter trains a two-stage system that first predicts the required reasoning budget and then enforces it through gradient-penalized reinforcement optimization.\n\nThinkSwitcher trains a supervised switching module that decides between concise and elaborate reasoning trajectories based on predicted task difficulty.\n\n## Reasoning Budgeting in 2026\n\nThinking effort should be treated as a tunable resource — measured in yield, governed by budgets, routed by difficulty, and surfaced as its own dashboard line item.\n\nModern models allow users to manually select from thinking modes, such as high/medium/low or thinking/fast modes, to balance performance and budget.\n\n## Accuracy and Latency Trade-offs\n\nAdaptive routing strategies prioritize lightweight models for simpler instances and selectively invoke higher-capacity models only when necessary, achieving both time efficiency and cost efficiency without compromising task performance.\n\nQuestion-driven routing classifies queries into discrete difficulty levels at the onset to assign reasoning strategies.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"abcf0954-ee6f-42aa-80d3-61c0426092ca","timestamp":"2026-06-21T06:43:28.592Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"adaptive reasoning effort routing reasoning models thinking budget 2025 2026 router accuracy latency","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01V9vMVeJUT2LgmXuhVEr62m","content":[{"title":"Adaptive Model and Strategy Routing for Cost-Efficient LLM Services | Proceedings of the ACM Web Conference 2026","url":"https://dl.acm.org/doi/abs/10.1145/3774904.3792556"},{"title":"Reasoning-Effort Budgeting: When Thinking Tokens Become a Finance Line Item - TianPan.co","url":"https://tianpan.co/blog/2026-04-27-reasoning-effort-budgeting-thinking-token-line-item"},{"title":"ARES: Adaptive Reasoning Effort Selection for Efficient LLM Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.07915"},{"title":"From Efficiency to Adaptivity: A Deeper Look at Adaptive Reasoning in Large Language Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.10788v2"},{"title":"SAT: Balancing Reasoning Accuracy and Efficiency with Stepwise Adaptive Thinking","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2604.07922v1"},{"title":"From Efficiency to Adaptivity: A Deeper Look at Adaptive Reasoning in Large Language Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2511.10788"},{"title":"Energy-Efficient Scaling of LLM Reasoning via Reinforced ...","url":"https://fi.ee.tsinghua.edu.cn/public/publications/08487c64-ff50-11f0-b382-2aaffa21d846.pdf"},{"title":"Towards Concise and Adaptive Thinking in Large Reasoning Models: A Survey","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2507.09662"}]},"I found several relevant research papers and articles on adaptive reasoning effort routing and related concepts from 2025-2026. Here are the key findings:\n\n## Adaptive Reasoning Effort Routing\n\nRTR (a routing system) dynamically assigns the most appropriate model pair during inference, enabling adaptive and cost-efficient reasoning tailored to query difficulty and budget scenarios.\n\n## Router Approaches and Models\n\nRouteLLM learns a lightweight router from preference data to dispatch easy inputs to cheaper small models and difficult ones to larger models, reducing total compute without degrading accuracy.\n\nSelfBudgeter trains a two-stage system that first predicts the required reasoning budget and then enforces it through gradient-penalized reinforcement optimization.\n\nThinkSwitcher trains a supervised switching module that decides between concise and elaborate reasoning trajectories based on predicted task difficulty.\n\n## Reasoning Budgeting in 2026\n\nThinking effort should be treated as a tunable resource — measured in yield, governed by budgets, routed by difficulty, and surfaced as its own dashboard line item.\n\nModern models allow users to manually select from thinking modes, such as high/medium/low or thinking/fast modes, to balance performance and budget.\n\n## Accuracy and Latency Trade-offs\n\nAdaptive routing strategies prioritize lightweight models for simpler instances and selectively invoke higher-capacity models only when necessary, achieving both time efficiency and cost efficiency without compromising task performance.\n\nQuestion-driven routing classifies queries into discrete difficulty levels at the onset to assign reasoning strategies."],"durationSeconds":9.494554708000273,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"47825c32-65ed-4c07-88e1-2d74d67b1643","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"28b18412-e62c-4bd0-b77f-321ee80ae543","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"32c7be0a-d03a-4f99-b63a-5bc0ac6e352a","agentId":"a2cceb1c12f4a6bcd","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01K3ZByLk485aunUp4pCQZYF","type":"tool_result","content":"# BaRP: LLM Routing with Bandit Feedback\n\n## Method Overview\nBaRP frames LLM routing as a **multi-objective contextual bandit problem**. The system encodes each prompt with a user preference vector specifying performance-cost tradeoffs, then uses policy gradients to learn which model to select. Key components include: a frozen sentence transformer for prompt encoding, an MLP for preference encoding, and a decision head producing logits over candidate LLMs.\n\n## Bandit Feedback Setup\nTraining occurs under realistic deployment constraints: \"only the outcome of the chosen model is observed\" rather than labels for all candidates. The framework randomly samples preference vectors during training to learn a single policy serving diverse user needs, simulating bandit conditions on pre-collected benchmark data.\n\n## Performance Gains vs. Baselines\n- **vs. strongest individual LLM**: 3.81% improvement on in-distribution tasks; 2.45% on out-of-distribution\n- **vs. offline routers** (RouterDC, GraphRouter): 12.46% and 25.99% improvements respectively\n- **Overall score**: 73.57% average on in-distribution tasks vs. 70.87% for largest LLM baseline\n- **Cost efficiency**: 50% cost reduction versus GraphRouter while improving score 16.84%\n\n## Cold-Start Handling\nThe paper doesn't explicitly address cold-start scenarios. Training uses pre-existing benchmark logs with complete information, then simulates bandit conditions. Generalization to unseen tasks is tested post-hoc rather than solving the cold-start problem directly.\n\n## Accuracy-Cost Tradeoffs\nThe preference vector enables real-time tuning without retraining:\n- At cost weight 0.2: $0.074 per query with 95%+ accuracy on ARC-C\n- At cost weight 0.8: $0.015 per query with moderate accuracy loss\n- \"Lower cost weights favor high performance at higher cost, while higher cost weights sacrifice some performance\" for substantial savings"}]},"uuid":"3816424a-dd89-4c1b-9b84-5ae230572d7c","timestamp":"2026-06-21T06:43:28.912Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":204252,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# BaRP: LLM Routing with Bandit Feedback\n\n## Method Overview\nBaRP frames LLM routing as a **multi-objective contextual bandit problem**. The system encodes each prompt with a user preference vector specifying performance-cost tradeoffs, then uses policy gradients to learn which model to select. Key components include: a frozen sentence transformer for prompt encoding, an MLP for preference encoding, and a decision head producing logits over candidate LLMs.\n\n## Bandit Feedback Setup\nTraining occurs under realistic deployment constraints: \"only the outcome of the chosen model is observed\" rather than labels for all candidates. The framework randomly samples preference vectors during training to learn a single policy serving diverse user needs, simulating bandit conditions on pre-collected benchmark data.\n\n## Performance Gains vs. Baselines\n- **vs. strongest individual LLM**: 3.81% improvement on in-distribution tasks; 2.45% on out-of-distribution\n- **vs. offline routers** (RouterDC, GraphRouter): 12.46% and 25.99% improvements respectively\n- **Overall score**: 73.57% average on in-distribution tasks vs. 70.87% for largest LLM baseline\n- **Cost efficiency**: 50% cost reduction versus GraphRouter while improving score 16.84%\n\n## Cold-Start Handling\nThe paper doesn't explicitly address cold-start scenarios. Training uses pre-existing benchmark logs with complete information, then simulates bandit conditions. Generalization to unseen tasks is tested post-hoc rather than solving the cold-start problem directly.\n\n## Accuracy-Cost Tradeoffs\nThe preference vector enables real-time tuning without retraining:\n- At cost weight 0.2: $0.074 per query with 95%+ accuracy on ARC-C\n- At cost weight 0.8: $0.015 per query with moderate accuracy loss\n- \"Lower cost weights favor high performance at higher cost, while higher cost weights sacrifice some performance\" for substantial savings","durationMs":7893,"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2510.07429v1"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"28b18412-e62c-4bd0-b77f-321ee80ae543","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"cba4a65c-16b3-4176-a771-a6ef7901beb4","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"32c7be0a-d03a-4f99-b63a-5bc0ac6e352a","agentId":"a2cceb1c12f4a6bcd","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0189SJXCmL3RepmVDmHJmLiC","type":"tool_result","content":"# LoRA/QLoRA Fine-Tuning on 16GB Apple Silicon Macs\n\n## Supported Model Sizes\n\nFor 16GB unified memory Macs, the guide specifies:\n- **LoRA (full precision):** 3B-7B models\n- **QLoRA (4-bit quantized):** 7B-8B models\n\n## Training Duration\n\nA 16GB M2 Pro can fine-tune an 8B model using QLoRA at approximately 200 tokens/second. For a typical 500-iteration training run on 300 examples, expect roughly 15-45 minutes total, though this varies based on sequence length and hardware specifics.\n\n## Memory Requirements\n\nQLoRA reduces memory usage by approximately 50% compared to full-precision LoRA. For an 8B model, QLoRA consumes around 7GB versus 14GB for standard LoRA, making QLoRA the necessary approach on 16GB systems.\n\n## Key Failure Modes\n\nThe document identifies several critical issues:\n\n1. **Memory exhaustion** — \"Yellow/red means the system is swapping, which destroys training speed\"\n2. **Data format errors** — Training loss won't decrease if examples use incorrect JSON structure or contain contradictory samples\n3. **Incompatible models** — Only Llama, Mistral, Qwen2, Phi, Gemma, Mixtral, OLMo, MiniCPM, and InternLM2 architectures work with MLX\n\n## Quality Consideration\n\nQLoRA produces \"slightly lower quality than full-precision LoRA because the base weights are approximated at 4-bit,\" though the practical difference remains small for most tasks."}]},"uuid":"d2b327e3-49b4-4bc6-a87f-bac9862bd17d","timestamp":"2026-06-21T06:43:29.511Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":41990,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# LoRA/QLoRA Fine-Tuning on 16GB Apple Silicon Macs\n\n## Supported Model Sizes\n\nFor 16GB unified memory Macs, the guide specifies:\n- **LoRA (full precision):** 3B-7B models\n- **QLoRA (4-bit quantized):** 7B-8B models\n\n## Training Duration\n\nA 16GB M2 Pro can fine-tune an 8B model using QLoRA at approximately 200 tokens/second. For a typical 500-iteration training run on 300 examples, expect roughly 15-45 minutes total, though this varies based on sequence length and hardware specifics.\n\n## Memory Requirements\n\nQLoRA reduces memory usage by approximately 50% compared to full-precision LoRA. For an 8B model, QLoRA consumes around 7GB versus 14GB for standard LoRA, making QLoRA the necessary approach on 16GB systems.\n\n## Key Failure Modes\n\nThe document identifies several critical issues:\n\n1. **Memory exhaustion** — \"Yellow/red means the system is swapping, which destroys training speed\"\n2. **Data format errors** — Training loss won't decrease if examples use incorrect JSON structure or contain contradictory samples\n3. **Incompatible models** — Only Llama, Mistral, Qwen2, Phi, Gemma, Mixtral, OLMo, MiniCPM, and InternLM2 architectures work with MLX\n\n## Quality Consideration\n\nQLoRA produces \"slightly lower quality than full-precision LoRA because the base weights are approximated at 4-bit,\" though the practical difference remains small for most tasks.","durationMs":6728,"url":"https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-mac-lora-mlx/"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"cba4a65c-16b3-4176-a771-a6ef7901beb4","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
