{"parentUuid":"70a433ac-e51c-46a7-91cc-d8ca06510ed0","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"32c7be0a-d03a-4f99-b63a-5bc0ac6e352a","agentId":"a2cceb1c12f4a6bcd","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01TsPtqqd9h935hGhXLBAmxY","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"ThinkSwitcher switch concise reasoning small reasoning model accuracy gains supervised router\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"From Efficiency to Adaptivity: A Deeper Look at Adaptive Reasoning in Large Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2511.10788\"},{\"title\":\"HRBench: Benchmarking and Understanding Thinking-Mode Switch Strategies in Hybrid-Reasoning LLMs\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2605.28398v1\"},{\"title\":\"Don’t Overthink It: A Survey of Efficient R1-style Large Reasoning Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02120v1\"},{\"title\":\"ThinkSwitcher: When to Think Hard, When to Think Fast\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.14183\"},{\"title\":\"ThinkSwitcher: When to Think Hard, When to Think Fast\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2505.14183v1\"},{\"title\":\"(PDF) Don't Overthink It: A Survey of Efficient R1-style Large Reasoning Models\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/394293544_Don't_Overthink_It_A_Survey_of_Efficient_R1-style_Large_Reasoning_Models\"},{\"title\":\"[Literature Review] ThinkSwitcher: When to Think Hard, When to Think Fast\",\"url\":\"https://www.themoonlight.io/en/review/thinkswitcher-when-to-think-hard-when-to-think-fast\"},{\"title\":\"Towards Concise and Adaptive Thinking in Large Reasoning Models: A Survey\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2507.09662v1\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - Eclipsess/Awesome-Efficient-Reasoning-LLMs: [TMLR 2025] Stop Overthinking: A Survey on Efficient Reasoning for Large Language Models · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/Eclipsess/Awesome-Efficient-Reasoning-LLMs\"},{\"title\":\"[2505.14183] ThinkSwitcher: When to Think Hard, When to Think Fast\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.14183\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about ThinkSwitcher:\n\n## Overview\n\nThinkSwitcher is a lightweight and adaptive framework that addresses the overthinking tendency in large reasoning models by dynamically selecting between short and long Chain-of-Thought (CoT) modes based on task complexity.\n\n## How It Works\n\nThinkSwitcher introduces a lightweight switching module trained with supervision signals derived from the relative performance of each reasoning mode across tasks. More specifically, given a query, it samples the responses of the query under both slow-thinking and fast-thinking mode via prompt engineering, and then calculates the pass rates of the query for each mode. A regressor is then trained with the pass rates as supervision target and the embedding extracted from LRMs as features.\n\n## Key Results\n\nThinkSwitcher reduces computational cost by 20–30% while preserving strong performance on complex tasks. Additionally, smaller models benefit disproportionately from adaptive switching. For example, on the 1.5B model, ThinkSwitcher reduces token usage by more than 30% while maintaining robust accuracy, suggesting that weaker models are more prone to over-elaboration and thus stand to gain more from selective short-form reasoning.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"7b76b056-e747-475a-bd8d-51cfd6933da5","timestamp":"2026-06-21T06:43:41.441Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"ThinkSwitcher switch concise reasoning small reasoning model accuracy gains supervised router","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_015SotEkFq9U3HvEnpSFy56z","content":[{"title":"From Efficiency to Adaptivity: A Deeper Look at Adaptive Reasoning in Large Language Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2511.10788"},{"title":"HRBench: Benchmarking and Understanding Thinking-Mode Switch Strategies in Hybrid-Reasoning LLMs","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2605.28398v1"},{"title":"Don’t Overthink It: A Survey of Efficient R1-style Large Reasoning Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2508.02120v1"},{"title":"ThinkSwitcher: When to Think Hard, When to Think Fast","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.14183"},{"title":"ThinkSwitcher: When to Think Hard, When to Think Fast","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2505.14183v1"},{"title":"(PDF) Don't Overthink It: A Survey of Efficient R1-style Large Reasoning Models","url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/394293544_Don't_Overthink_It_A_Survey_of_Efficient_R1-style_Large_Reasoning_Models"},{"title":"[Literature Review] ThinkSwitcher: When to Think Hard, When to Think Fast","url":"https://www.themoonlight.io/en/review/thinkswitcher-when-to-think-hard-when-to-think-fast"},{"title":"Towards Concise and Adaptive Thinking in Large Reasoning Models: A Survey","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2507.09662v1"},{"title":"GitHub - Eclipsess/Awesome-Efficient-Reasoning-LLMs: [TMLR 2025] Stop Overthinking: A Survey on Efficient Reasoning for Large Language Models · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/Eclipsess/Awesome-Efficient-Reasoning-LLMs"},{"title":"[2505.14183] ThinkSwitcher: When to Think Hard, When to Think Fast","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.14183"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about ThinkSwitcher:\n\n## Overview\n\nThinkSwitcher is a lightweight and adaptive framework that addresses the overthinking tendency in large reasoning models by dynamically selecting between short and long Chain-of-Thought (CoT) modes based on task complexity.\n\n## How It Works\n\nThinkSwitcher introduces a lightweight switching module trained with supervision signals derived from the relative performance of each reasoning mode across tasks. More specifically, given a query, it samples the responses of the query under both slow-thinking and fast-thinking mode via prompt engineering, and then calculates the pass rates of the query for each mode. A regressor is then trained with the pass rates as supervision target and the embedding extracted from LRMs as features.\n\n## Key Results\n\nThinkSwitcher reduces computational cost by 20–30% while preserving strong performance on complex tasks. Additionally, smaller models benefit disproportionately from adaptive switching. For example, on the 1.5B model, ThinkSwitcher reduces token usage by more than 30% while maintaining robust accuracy, suggesting that weaker models are more prone to over-elaboration and thus stand to gain more from selective short-form reasoning."],"durationSeconds":7.176024334000424,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"70a433ac-e51c-46a7-91cc-d8ca06510ed0","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"029661c7-4ee4-41b2-ae67-dfa3cd93e420","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"32c7be0a-d03a-4f99-b63a-5bc0ac6e352a","agentId":"a2cceb1c12f4a6bcd","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01VvzTpUxp5FpYFJftGQ45oJ","type":"tool_result","content":"# Adaptive Reasoning: Switching Between Thinking Modes\n\n## Overview\nThe survey discusses methods that dynamically allocate reasoning effort, switching between deliberate and fast inference modes based on task complexity.\n\n## Categorical Organization\n\n**Training-based routing** learns decision policies during training:\n- RouteLLM dispatches queries to small or large models based on difficulty\n- ThinkSwitcher trains a module to \"decide between concise and elaborate reasoning trajectories\"\n- AdaMOE uses null experts to skip computation for tokens needing no reasoning\n\n**Training-free routing** applies inference-time control without retraining:\n- Entropy-based halting stops when uncertainty drops below thresholds\n- Answer convergence detection terminates when intermediate results stabilize\n- Adaptive sampling adjusts breadth based on confidence signals\n\n## Performance Metrics\n\nThe document provides **no specific accuracy or token savings numbers** for router comparisons against always-think/always-no-think baselines. While it mentions that routers \"reduc[e] total compute without degrading accuracy,\" concrete metrics aren't included.\n\n## Qwen-Specific Data\n\nThe survey contains **no information about Qwen's thinking/no-thinking mode switching** or performance metrics.\n\nThe taxonomy emphasizes that routing mechanisms exist across both training paradigms, but empirical quantification remains absent from this particular survey document."}]},"uuid":"f7520065-95d3-4c47-af12-42eb42fb3b02","timestamp":"2026-06-21T06:43:41.625Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":268874,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Adaptive Reasoning: Switching Between Thinking Modes\n\n## Overview\nThe survey discusses methods that dynamically allocate reasoning effort, switching between deliberate and fast inference modes based on task complexity.\n\n## Categorical Organization\n\n**Training-based routing** learns decision policies during training:\n- RouteLLM dispatches queries to small or large models based on difficulty\n- ThinkSwitcher trains a module to \"decide between concise and elaborate reasoning trajectories\"\n- AdaMOE uses null experts to skip computation for tokens needing no reasoning\n\n**Training-free routing** applies inference-time control without retraining:\n- Entropy-based halting stops when uncertainty drops below thresholds\n- Answer convergence detection terminates when intermediate results stabilize\n- Adaptive sampling adjusts breadth based on confidence signals\n\n## Performance Metrics\n\nThe document provides **no specific accuracy or token savings numbers** for router comparisons against always-think/always-no-think baselines. While it mentions that routers \"reduc[e] total compute without degrading accuracy,\" concrete metrics aren't included.\n\n## Qwen-Specific Data\n\nThe survey contains **no information about Qwen's thinking/no-thinking mode switching** or performance metrics.\n\nThe taxonomy emphasizes that routing mechanisms exist across both training paradigms, but empirical quantification remains absent from this particular survey document.","durationMs":5611,"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.10788v2"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"029661c7-4ee4-41b2-ae67-dfa3cd93e420","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"9b388f35-8051-484d-87fa-0541d955c398","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"32c7be0a-d03a-4f99-b63a-5bc0ac6e352a","agentId":"a2cceb1c12f4a6bcd","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RnJwsVUJbvFxED4Pfwt487","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"small LLM distillation catastrophic forgetting LoRA overfitting small dataset domain specific 2024 2025\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Knowledge Distillation of Large Language Models for Use ...\",\"url\":\"https://elib.dlr.de/220552/1/Masterthesis%20Konstantin%20Witossek.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Knowledge distillation and dataset distillation of large language models: emerging trends, challenges, and future directions - PMC\",\"url\":\"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12634706/\"},{\"title\":\"Diabetica: Adapting Large Language Model to Enhance Multiple Medical   Tasks in Diabetes Care and Management\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2409.13191\"},{\"title\":\"How to Alleviate Catastrophic Forgetting in LLMs Finetuning?   Hierarchical Layer-Wise and Element-Wise Regularization\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2501.13669\"},{\"title\":\"How to Alleviate Catastrophic Forgetting in LLMs Finetuning? Hierarchical Layer-Wise and Element-Wise Regularization\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2501.13669v2\"},{\"title\":\"Advancing Model Refinement: Muon-Optimized Distillation and Quantization for LLM Deployment\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2601.09865v1\"},{\"title\":\"A Survey on Knowledge Distillation of Large Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2402.13116\"},{\"title\":\"Demystifying LLM Variants: Fine-Tuning, Distillation, and Quantization Explained | by Ashutosh Dongaonkar | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@ashu_don/demystifying-llm-variants-fine-tuning-distillation-and-quantization-explained-816b4d96db06\"},{\"title\":\"Fine-Tuning LLMs: Overcoming Catastrophic Forgetting\",\"url\":\"https://www.legionintel.com/blog/navigating-the-challenges-of-fine-tuning-and-catastrophic-forgetting\"},{\"title\":\"Modular Multi-Task Learning for Chemical Reaction Prediction\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2602.10404\"}]\n\nI've successfully retrieved search results related to your query about small LLM distillation, catastrophic forgetting, LoRA, overfitting on small datasets, and domain-specific fine-tuning. Here are the key findings:\n\n## Key Research Areas and Findings\n\n**Catastrophic Forgetting and Domain-Specific Fine-Tuning**\n\nFine-tuning LLMs with domain-specific data improves performance in that domain but results in decreased generalization across other domains because of overfitting or catastrophic forgetting. Limited data can result in overfitting.\n\n**LoRA and Catastrophic Forgetting**\n\nFull parameter fine-tuning updates all model parameters to improve task adaptability but often causes catastrophic forgetting, while PEFT methods like LoRA reduce computational costs and mitigate forgetting by updating only a small subset of parameters through low-rank matrices, though some forgetting still occurs. However, significant drops in performance on previous datasets have been observed when applying LoRA for fine-tuning language models on sequential datasets.\n\n**Mitigation Strategies**\n\nLoRA training combined with self-distillation can mitigate catastrophic forgetting, as LoRA reduces trainable parameters through low-rank decomposition while self-distillation maintains the model's original distribution. Data augmentation techniques such as synthetic data generation and transfer learning can improve domain-specific performance while maintaining generalization accuracy.\n\n**Distillation and Small Datasets**\n\nBy creating a distilled subset of domain-specific data, researchers can rapidly adapt large-scale LLMs to specialized tasks without incurring the full computational cost. LoRA complements knowledge distillation by enabling student models to adapt to teacher-generated data without overfitting or catastrophic forgetting.\n\nThe research spans recent 2024-2025 work addressing these interconnected challenges in LLM adaptation.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"9b0fa191-7381-41d1-99d7-474d03e6b9d4","timestamp":"2026-06-21T06:43:45.448Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"small LLM distillation catastrophic forgetting LoRA overfitting small dataset domain specific 2024 2025","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01FWk2mmBvQ4aw3BH7ys9MEd","content":[{"title":"Knowledge Distillation of Large Language Models for Use ...","url":"https://elib.dlr.de/220552/1/Masterthesis%20Konstantin%20Witossek.pdf"},{"title":"Knowledge distillation and dataset distillation of large language models: emerging trends, challenges, and future directions - PMC","url":"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12634706/"},{"title":"Diabetica: Adapting Large Language Model to Enhance Multiple Medical   Tasks in Diabetes Care and Management","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2409.13191"},{"title":"How to Alleviate Catastrophic Forgetting in LLMs Finetuning?   Hierarchical Layer-Wise and Element-Wise Regularization","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2501.13669"},{"title":"How to Alleviate Catastrophic Forgetting in LLMs Finetuning? Hierarchical Layer-Wise and Element-Wise Regularization","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2501.13669v2"},{"title":"Advancing Model Refinement: Muon-Optimized Distillation and Quantization for LLM Deployment","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2601.09865v1"},{"title":"A Survey on Knowledge Distillation of Large Language Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2402.13116"},{"title":"Demystifying LLM Variants: Fine-Tuning, Distillation, and Quantization Explained | by Ashutosh Dongaonkar | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@ashu_don/demystifying-llm-variants-fine-tuning-distillation-and-quantization-explained-816b4d96db06"},{"title":"Fine-Tuning LLMs: Overcoming Catastrophic Forgetting","url":"https://www.legionintel.com/blog/navigating-the-challenges-of-fine-tuning-and-catastrophic-forgetting"},{"title":"Modular Multi-Task Learning for Chemical Reaction Prediction","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2602.10404"}]},"I've successfully retrieved search results related to your query about small LLM distillation, catastrophic forgetting, LoRA, overfitting on small datasets, and domain-specific fine-tuning. Here are the key findings:\n\n## Key Research Areas and Findings\n\n**Catastrophic Forgetting and Domain-Specific Fine-Tuning**\n\nFine-tuning LLMs with domain-specific data improves performance in that domain but results in decreased generalization across other domains because of overfitting or catastrophic forgetting. Limited data can result in overfitting.\n\n**LoRA and Catastrophic Forgetting**\n\nFull parameter fine-tuning updates all model parameters to improve task adaptability but often causes catastrophic forgetting, while PEFT methods like LoRA reduce computational costs and mitigate forgetting by updating only a small subset of parameters through low-rank matrices, though some forgetting still occurs. However, significant drops in performance on previous datasets have been observed when applying LoRA for fine-tuning language models on sequential datasets.\n\n**Mitigation Strategies**\n\nLoRA training combined with self-distillation can mitigate catastrophic forgetting, as LoRA reduces trainable parameters through low-rank decomposition while self-distillation maintains the model's original distribution. Data augmentation techniques such as synthetic data generation and transfer learning can improve domain-specific performance while maintaining generalization accuracy.\n\n**Distillation and Small Datasets**\n\nBy creating a distilled subset of domain-specific data, researchers can rapidly adapt large-scale LLMs to specialized tasks without incurring the full computational cost. LoRA complements knowledge distillation by enabling student models to adapt to teacher-generated data without overfitting or catastrophic forgetting.\n\nThe research spans recent 2024-2025 work addressing these interconnected challenges in LLM adaptation."],"durationSeconds":9.011025125000625,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"9b388f35-8051-484d-87fa-0541d955c398","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
