{"parentUuid":"bc34bd28-5e00-4e39-bba3-563b0e22a2a1","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"32c7be0a-d03a-4f99-b63a-5bc0ac6e352a","agentId":"a2cceb1c12f4a6bcd","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01AvA8mof9Z2tA6LcAa3ym3w","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"MLX run two models concurrently memory unified Apple silicon serve adapter plus embedding model 16GB\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Unified Memory — MLX 0.31.2 documentation\",\"url\":\"https://ml-explore.github.io/mlx/build/html/usage/unified_memory.html\"},{\"title\":\"Exploring LLMs with MLX and the Neural Accelerators in the M5 GPU - Apple Machine Learning Research\",\"url\":\"https://machinelearning.apple.com/research/exploring-llms-mlx-m5\"},{\"title\":\"Explore large language models on Apple silicon with MLX - WWDC25 - Videos - Apple Developer\",\"url\":\"https://developer.apple.com/videos/play/wwdc2025/298/\"},{\"title\":\"Native LLM and MLLM Inference at Scale on Apple Silicon\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2601.19139v1\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - ml-explore/mlx: MLX: An array framework for Apple silicon · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx\"},{\"title\":\"Run Local Agentic AI on Mac With MLX [2026 Guide]\",\"url\":\"https://www.kunalganglani.com/blog/run-local-agentic-ai-mac-mlx\"},{\"title\":\"Get started with MLX for Apple silicon - WWDC25 - Videos - Apple Developer\",\"url\":\"https://developer.apple.com/videos/play/wwdc2025/315/\"},{\"title\":\"Ollama is supercharged by MLX's unified memory use on Apple Silicon\",\"url\":\"https://appleinsider.com/articles/26/03/31/ollama-is-supercharged-by-mlxs-unified-memory-use-on-apple-silicon\"},{\"title\":\"Request: Support for concurrent inference of independent models from separate threads · Issue #3078 · ml-explore/mlx\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx/issues/3078\"},{\"title\":\"Apple Open Source\",\"url\":\"https://opensource.apple.com/projects/mlx/\"}]\n\nI found search results related to MLX on Apple Silicon. Based on your specific query about running two models concurrently with a serve adapter plus embedding model on 16GB unified memory, here's what I found:\n\n## Key Findings:\n\n**Unified Memory Architecture:** Apple silicon has a unified memory architecture where the CPU and GPU have direct access to the same memory pool. Operations can run in parallel since there are no dependencies between them.\n\n**Concurrent Model Execution Challenges:** There is an active discussion in the MLX community about this exact use case. A developer building an application that runs two independent ML models concurrently on Apple Silicon found that each model processes different inputs and produces different outputs with no shared arrays or dependencies between them. However, this currently crashes due to thread-safety issues in the Metal backend.\n\n**Memory Requirements:** For context on 16GB unified memory, with 16 GB unified memory (M1, M2, M3 base), neither Gemma 4 26B nor Qwen3 35B will fit, and you should look at smaller models like Gemma 4 12B or Qwen3 8B.\n\n**MLX Capabilities:** Key advantages of MLX for inference include true zero-copy operations that exploit unified memory, lazy evaluation that fuses operations and reduces memory allocation overhead, and native quantization support with efficient dequantization kernels.\n\nThe search results indicate that while MLX is well-optimized for Apple Silicon's unified memory, concurrent multi-model inference on separate threads remains an open technical challenge that the MLX team is actively working to address.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"7d37d846-b47a-4b97-8998-86a6aa43c4fe","timestamp":"2026-06-21T06:43:59.734Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"MLX run two models concurrently memory unified Apple silicon serve adapter plus embedding model 16GB","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_015XyqjRAMr1puEWsFboFGax","content":[{"title":"Unified Memory — MLX 0.31.2 documentation","url":"https://ml-explore.github.io/mlx/build/html/usage/unified_memory.html"},{"title":"Exploring LLMs with MLX and the Neural Accelerators in the M5 GPU - Apple Machine Learning Research","url":"https://machinelearning.apple.com/research/exploring-llms-mlx-m5"},{"title":"Explore large language models on Apple silicon with MLX - WWDC25 - Videos - Apple Developer","url":"https://developer.apple.com/videos/play/wwdc2025/298/"},{"title":"Native LLM and MLLM Inference at Scale on Apple Silicon","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2601.19139v1"},{"title":"GitHub - ml-explore/mlx: MLX: An array framework for Apple silicon · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx"},{"title":"Run Local Agentic AI on Mac With MLX [2026 Guide]","url":"https://www.kunalganglani.com/blog/run-local-agentic-ai-mac-mlx"},{"title":"Get started with MLX for Apple silicon - WWDC25 - Videos - Apple Developer","url":"https://developer.apple.com/videos/play/wwdc2025/315/"},{"title":"Ollama is supercharged by MLX's unified memory use on Apple Silicon","url":"https://appleinsider.com/articles/26/03/31/ollama-is-supercharged-by-mlxs-unified-memory-use-on-apple-silicon"},{"title":"Request: Support for concurrent inference of independent models from separate threads · Issue #3078 · ml-explore/mlx","url":"https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx/issues/3078"},{"title":"Apple Open Source","url":"https://opensource.apple.com/projects/mlx/"}]},"I found search results related to MLX on Apple Silicon. Based on your specific query about running two models concurrently with a serve adapter plus embedding model on 16GB unified memory, here's what I found:\n\n## Key Findings:\n\n**Unified Memory Architecture:** Apple silicon has a unified memory architecture where the CPU and GPU have direct access to the same memory pool. Operations can run in parallel since there are no dependencies between them.\n\n**Concurrent Model Execution Challenges:** There is an active discussion in the MLX community about this exact use case. A developer building an application that runs two independent ML models concurrently on Apple Silicon found that each model processes different inputs and produces different outputs with no shared arrays or dependencies between them. However, this currently crashes due to thread-safety issues in the Metal backend.\n\n**Memory Requirements:** For context on 16GB unified memory, with 16 GB unified memory (M1, M2, M3 base), neither Gemma 4 26B nor Qwen3 35B will fit, and you should look at smaller models like Gemma 4 12B or Qwen3 8B.\n\n**MLX Capabilities:** Key advantages of MLX for inference include true zero-copy operations that exploit unified memory, lazy evaluation that fuses operations and reduces memory allocation overhead, and native quantization support with efficient dequantization kernels.\n\nThe search results indicate that while MLX is well-optimized for Apple Silicon's unified memory, concurrent multi-model inference on separate threads remains an open technical challenge that the MLX team is actively working to address."],"durationSeconds":7.344822209000587,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"bc34bd28-5e00-4e39-bba3-563b0e22a2a1","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"40c12eae-13a9-4ee8-b50e-f2728dbb8336","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"32c7be0a-d03a-4f99-b63a-5bc0ac6e352a","agentId":"a2cceb1c12f4a6bcd","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01421GfxtvuUBoFSmNxw14Mm","type":"tool_result","content":"# ThinkSwitcher: Decision Mechanism and Performance\n\n## Switching Method\n\nThinkSwitcher employs a lightweight regressor that dynamically selects between reasoning modes. The decision rule compares predicted performance margins: \"long CoT pathway is selected when its predicted advantage over short CoT exceeds the threshold τ\" (equation-based routing with tunable threshold).\n\n## Supervision Signal\n\nThe framework uses **empirical pass rates** as supervision. For each training query, it generates k=8 responses under both short and long CoT modes, evaluates correctness, and computes pass rates: P_m(q) = (1/k)∑I[responses correct]. These continuous targets (values 0-1) directly supervise the switcher's predictions.\n\n## Training Objective\n\nA margin-aware loss combines two components:\n1. **MSE loss** on individual mode predictions\n2. **Margin loss**: \"penalizes the error in the predicted difference\" between modes\n\nThis directly aligns training with the routing mechanism, where decisions depend on y_LC - y_SC.\n\n## Models Tested\n\nThree DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen models: 1.5B, 7B, and 14B parameters.\n\n## Key Performance Numbers\n\n**7B model results** (representative):\n- LC-Only baseline: 64.6% avg accuracy, 7,617 tokens\n- ThinkSwitcher: 62.8% accuracy, 5,405 tokens (~29% token reduction, ~2% accuracy drop)\n- SC-Only baseline: 46.0% accuracy, 1,079 tokens\n\nOn GSM8K specifically: 30% token savings with <1% accuracy loss.\n\n## Lightweight Architecture\n\nThe switcher is \"a Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP) consisting of 5 linear layers\" with hidden dimensions [1024, 768, 512, 256, 2]. Computational overhead is negligible: ~10M FLOPs per query versus ~100T for LLM decoding.\n\n## Data Collection / Cold Start\n\nTraining data aggregates: MATH, GSM8K training splits, historical AIME problems (1983-2023), and Omni-MATH subsets (~3,900 problems). No overlap with test sets. The approach requires sampling multiple responses per question during training (expensive), but no additional fine-tuning of the backbone model."}]},"uuid":"a35c3fef-87c8-49c2-816d-eedeb6e1a537","timestamp":"2026-06-21T06:44:01.177Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":328209,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# ThinkSwitcher: Decision Mechanism and Performance\n\n## Switching Method\n\nThinkSwitcher employs a lightweight regressor that dynamically selects between reasoning modes. The decision rule compares predicted performance margins: \"long CoT pathway is selected when its predicted advantage over short CoT exceeds the threshold τ\" (equation-based routing with tunable threshold).\n\n## Supervision Signal\n\nThe framework uses **empirical pass rates** as supervision. For each training query, it generates k=8 responses under both short and long CoT modes, evaluates correctness, and computes pass rates: P_m(q) = (1/k)∑I[responses correct]. These continuous targets (values 0-1) directly supervise the switcher's predictions.\n\n## Training Objective\n\nA margin-aware loss combines two components:\n1. **MSE loss** on individual mode predictions\n2. **Margin loss**: \"penalizes the error in the predicted difference\" between modes\n\nThis directly aligns training with the routing mechanism, where decisions depend on y_LC - y_SC.\n\n## Models Tested\n\nThree DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen models: 1.5B, 7B, and 14B parameters.\n\n## Key Performance Numbers\n\n**7B model results** (representative):\n- LC-Only baseline: 64.6% avg accuracy, 7,617 tokens\n- ThinkSwitcher: 62.8% accuracy, 5,405 tokens (~29% token reduction, ~2% accuracy drop)\n- SC-Only baseline: 46.0% accuracy, 1,079 tokens\n\nOn GSM8K specifically: 30% token savings with <1% accuracy loss.\n\n## Lightweight Architecture\n\nThe switcher is \"a Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP) consisting of 5 linear layers\" with hidden dimensions [1024, 768, 512, 256, 2]. Computational overhead is negligible: ~10M FLOPs per query versus ~100T for LLM decoding.\n\n## Data Collection / Cold Start\n\nTraining data aggregates: MATH, GSM8K training splits, historical AIME problems (1983-2023), and Omni-MATH subsets (~3,900 problems). No overlap with test sets. The approach requires sampling multiple responses per question during training (expensive), but no additional fine-tuning of the backbone model.","durationMs":9430,"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2505.14183v1"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"40c12eae-13a9-4ee8-b50e-f2728dbb8336","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"a35c3fef-87c8-49c2-816d-eedeb6e1a537","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a2cceb1c12f4a6bcd","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_015shjJHx2nupBXQRxWzhtG5","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have comprehensive material on both candidates. The ThinkSwitcher finding is especially load-bearing — it maps almost exactly to Yogi's existing Think/NoThink navigator and uses an outcome-based (pass-rate) signal. Let me do one final check on Qwen3 think/no-think mode mechanics and routing cold-start to ground the recommendation."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1293,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1183,"cache_read_input_tokens":23894,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1183,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFxBfVDZzR8rESnwAyvw","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"584d4f22-415e-4bc8-a8b4-edc27caab130","timestamp":"2026-06-21T06:44:05.522Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"584d4f22-415e-4bc8-a8b4-edc27caab130","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a2cceb1c12f4a6bcd","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_015shjJHx2nupBXQRxWzhtG5","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01KkP2DSAm9NS5XrK5U3mu9z","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"Qwen3 enable_thinking no_think hybrid reasoning mode toggle /think /no_think"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1293,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1183,"cache_read_input_tokens":23894,"output_tokens":205,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1183},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1293,"output_tokens":205,"cache_read_input_tokens":23894,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1183,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1183,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFxBfVDZzR8rESnwAyvw","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"50e536f0-24e9-46e2-a04e-8eee1e5b5474","timestamp":"2026-06-21T06:44:06.143Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"50e536f0-24e9-46e2-a04e-8eee1e5b5474","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"32c7be0a-d03a-4f99-b63a-5bc0ac6e352a","agentId":"a2cceb1c12f4a6bcd","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01KkP2DSAm9NS5XrK5U3mu9z","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Qwen3 enable_thinking no_think hybrid reasoning mode toggle /think /no_think\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Qwen3: Think Deeper, Act Faster | Hybrid Thinking AI Model\",\"url\":\"https://qwen3.app/\"},{\"title\":\"Qwen 3.5 Model: Switching Between Thinking and Non-Thinking · Issue #1559 · lmstudio-ai/lmstudio-bug-tracker\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/lmstudio-ai/lmstudio-bug-tracker/issues/1559\"},{\"title\":\"Qwen3: Run a Thinking LLM Locally with One Command\",\"url\":\"https://learnopencv.com/qwen3/\"},{\"title\":\"Qwen/Qwen3-32B · Hugging Face\",\"url\":\"https://huggingface.co/Qwen/Qwen3-32B\"},{\"title\":\"Using deep thinking models - Alibaba Cloud Model Studio - Alibaba Cloud Documentation Center\",\"url\":\"https://www.alibabacloud.com/help/en/model-studio/deep-thinking\"},{\"title\":\"Deployment example for a qwen3 model with hybrid thinking - Reasoning Outputs - vLLM Forums\",\"url\":\"https://discuss.vllm.ai/t/deployment-example-for-a-qwen3-model-with-hybrid-thinking/1462\"},{\"title\":\"Qwen3 - Unified Models for Thinking and Non-Thinking\",\"url\":\"https://debuggercafe.com/qwen3-unified-models-for-thinking-and-non-thinking/\"},{\"title\":\"Qwen/Qwen3-VL-30B-A3B-Thinking · Disable thinking\",\"url\":\"https://huggingface.co/Qwen/Qwen3-VL-30B-A3B-Thinking/discussions/7\"},{\"title\":\"Qwen3.5 - How to Run Locally | Unsloth Documentation\",\"url\":\"https://unsloth.ai/docs/models/qwen3.5\"},{\"title\":\"unsloth/Qwen3.5-9B-GGUF · Enabling or disabling reasoning (default is disabled)\",\"url\":\"https://huggingface.co/unsloth/Qwen3.5-9B-GGUF/discussions/2\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's comprehensive information about Qwen3's hybrid reasoning mode toggle features:\n\n## Qwen3 Hybrid Reasoning Mode Control\n\nYou can control Qwen3's thinking modes through the 'enable_thinking' parameter when using the models. Setting it to True enables in-depth reasoning, while False provides quicker responses.\n\n### Toggle Methods\n\nQwen3 offers two main ways to control reasoning modes:\n\n1. **Global Parameter**: Enable globally (enable_thinking=True/False) or per turn (/think, /no_think).\n\n2. **Per-Turn Dynamic Switching**: You can also use '/think' and '/no_think' commands within prompts to dynamically switch between modes during multi-turn conversations.\n\n### Implementation Details\n\nWhen explicitly setting enable_thinking=True or leaving it as the default value in tokenizer.apply_chat_template, the model will engage its thinking mode. In this mode, the model will generate think content wrapped in a <think>...</think> block, followed by the final response.\n\n### Reasoning Modes\n\nThinking Mode shows a full <think> chain of thought, uses a broader search, and has higher accuracy. The model performs internal step-by-thought reasoning (often using latent Chain-of-Thought) before generating the final answer. Fast Mode hides the steps, replies instantly. The model provides a direct, faster response, suitable for simpler queries where latency is critical.\n\n### Thinking Budget\n\nUsers can specify a \"thinking budget\" (e.g., a maximum number of tokens for the thinking process). This helps balance latency and performance based on the complexity of the task, effectively controlling the \"depth\" of reasoning.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"52fd10fa-1da0-4cb7-b554-0185b3f22eb0","timestamp":"2026-06-21T06:44:14.305Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"Qwen3 enable_thinking no_think hybrid reasoning mode toggle /think /no_think","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01JPghx9DLosFdAQ4WAQBPqS","content":[{"title":"Qwen3: Think Deeper, Act Faster | Hybrid Thinking AI Model","url":"https://qwen3.app/"},{"title":"Qwen 3.5 Model: Switching Between Thinking and Non-Thinking · Issue #1559 · lmstudio-ai/lmstudio-bug-tracker","url":"https://github.com/lmstudio-ai/lmstudio-bug-tracker/issues/1559"},{"title":"Qwen3: Run a Thinking LLM Locally with One Command","url":"https://learnopencv.com/qwen3/"},{"title":"Qwen/Qwen3-32B · Hugging Face","url":"https://huggingface.co/Qwen/Qwen3-32B"},{"title":"Using deep thinking models - Alibaba Cloud Model Studio - Alibaba Cloud Documentation Center","url":"https://www.alibabacloud.com/help/en/model-studio/deep-thinking"},{"title":"Deployment example for a qwen3 model with hybrid thinking - Reasoning Outputs - vLLM Forums","url":"https://discuss.vllm.ai/t/deployment-example-for-a-qwen3-model-with-hybrid-thinking/1462"},{"title":"Qwen3 - Unified Models for Thinking and Non-Thinking","url":"https://debuggercafe.com/qwen3-unified-models-for-thinking-and-non-thinking/"},{"title":"Qwen/Qwen3-VL-30B-A3B-Thinking · Disable thinking","url":"https://huggingface.co/Qwen/Qwen3-VL-30B-A3B-Thinking/discussions/7"},{"title":"Qwen3.5 - How to Run Locally | Unsloth Documentation","url":"https://unsloth.ai/docs/models/qwen3.5"},{"title":"unsloth/Qwen3.5-9B-GGUF · Enabling or disabling reasoning (default is disabled)","url":"https://huggingface.co/unsloth/Qwen3.5-9B-GGUF/discussions/2"}]},"Based on the search results, here's comprehensive information about Qwen3's hybrid reasoning mode toggle features:\n\n## Qwen3 Hybrid Reasoning Mode Control\n\nYou can control Qwen3's thinking modes through the 'enable_thinking' parameter when using the models. Setting it to True enables in-depth reasoning, while False provides quicker responses.\n\n### Toggle Methods\n\nQwen3 offers two main ways to control reasoning modes:\n\n1. **Global Parameter**: Enable globally (enable_thinking=True/False) or per turn (/think, /no_think).\n\n2. **Per-Turn Dynamic Switching**: You can also use '/think' and '/no_think' commands within prompts to dynamically switch between modes during multi-turn conversations.\n\n### Implementation Details\n\nWhen explicitly setting enable_thinking=True or leaving it as the default value in tokenizer.apply_chat_template, the model will engage its thinking mode. In this mode, the model will generate think content wrapped in a <think>...</think> block, followed by the final response.\n\n### Reasoning Modes\n\nThinking Mode shows a full <think> chain of thought, uses a broader search, and has higher accuracy. The model performs internal step-by-thought reasoning (often using latent Chain-of-Thought) before generating the final answer. Fast Mode hides the steps, replies instantly. The model provides a direct, faster response, suitable for simpler queries where latency is critical.\n\n### Thinking Budget\n\nUsers can specify a \"thinking budget\" (e.g., a maximum number of tokens for the thinking process). This helps balance latency and performance based on the complexity of the task, effectively controlling the \"depth\" of reasoning."],"durationSeconds":7.954441333999857,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"50e536f0-24e9-46e2-a04e-8eee1e5b5474","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"52fd10fa-1da0-4cb7-b554-0185b3f22eb0","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a2cceb1c12f4a6bcd","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011BQqNoksyv8BdXQWxJRQjh","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have everything needed. Here are my findings.\n\n---\n\n# Yogi's next compounding layer: distillation vs. outcome-learned routing\n\n## Bottom line\n\n**Build outcome-learned routing next.** It is the natural, low-risk extension of the Think/NoThink navigator you've already certified, it fits the 16 GB / one-model-at-a-time constraint with zero memory pressure, it has direct 2025-2026 research backing (ThinkSwitcher is almost exactly your navigator), and it can run *inside the existing automated loop* because the router itself does no model inference. Per-domain weight distillation is feasible on your hardware but is a much heavier bet with real downside risk (forgetting, overfit, build-loop violations) and should be deferred to its M3 slot.\n\n---\n\n## Candidate (i): Per-domain weight distillation within 16 GB\n\n### Feasibility — yes, the memory math works\n- QLoRA on an 8B model fits comfortably: the 4-bit base stays quantized and only adapter weights are full precision. Reported footprint is **~7 GB for QLoRA 8B vs ~14 GB for full-precision LoRA 8B** on a 16 GB Mac; QLoRA is the *necessary* path at 16 GB. ([insiderllm.com guide](https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-mac-lora-mlx/))\n- General QLoRA math agrees: 4-bit NF4 + double quantization cuts base-weight memory ~75% vs fp16; 7B QLoRA fits in ~12 GB and aggressive paged-optimizer setups push an 8B down toward ~6 GB. Plain LoRA (no quant) on 8B needs ~16 GB. ([lyceum.technology VRAM math](https://lyceum.technology/magazine/lora-vs-full-fine-tuning-memory-cost/), [Modal VRAM guide](https://modal.com/blog/how-much-vram-need-fine-tuning))\n- Apple-silicon path is mature: **MLX-LM** auto-runs QLoRA when you pass a 4-bit base with `--train`, supports Qwen2 architecture, and there are Unsloth-compatible MLX wrappers (mlx-tune). ([MLX-LM run/fine-tune guide](https://markaicode.com/run-fine-tune-llms-mac-mlx-lm/), [mlx-tune](https://github.com/ARahim3/mlx-tune))\n\n### Realistic time / quality\n- A 500-iteration run on ~300 examples at ~200 tok/s on a 16 GB M2 Pro is **~15-45 min**. That's per-domain, repeated as data accrues. ([insiderllm.com guide](https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-mac-lora-mlx/))\n- QLoRA quality is \"slightly lower than full-precision LoRA because the base is 4-bit,\" small in practice. ([insiderllm.com guide](https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-mac-lora-mlx/))\n\n### Concurrent inference + nomic\n- Unified memory means a 4-bit student/adapter (~5-6 GB for an 8B base, much less for a 0.5-3B student) plus `nomic-embed-text` (~0.3 GB) physically fits in 16 GB. But **MLX currently crashes on truly concurrent inference of two independent models from separate threads** (Metal backend thread-safety, open issue #3078). In practice you'd serialize: embed, then generate — which is what Ollama already does anyway. ([MLX unified memory](https://ml-explore.github.io/mlx/build/html/usage/unified_memory.html), [MLX issue #3078](https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx/issues/3078))\n\n### Failure modes (the real cost)\n- **Catastrophic forgetting**: domain fine-tuning improves the target domain but degrades general capability; LoRA *mitigates but does not eliminate* forgetting, and sequential LoRA fine-tunes show real drops on prior data. ([arXiv 2501.13669](https://arxiv.org/html/2501.13669v2), [survey PMC12634706](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12634706/))\n- **Tiny-data overfit**: 200-500 examples is exactly the regime where overfit/contradictory-sample failures appear; mitigations (synthetic data, self-distillation) add machinery. ([insiderllm.com guide](https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-mac-lora-mlx/), [arXiv 2402.13116 distillation survey](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2402.13116))\n- **Build-loop conflict**: training *is* heavy model inference. Your CLAUDE.md HARD RULE forbids model inference in the automated loop and forbids background heavy jobs — so any distillation cycle must be foreground/user-initiated, and you need eval gating so a regressed adapter never ships. That's a lot of safety scaffolding for the first weight-layer.\n\n**When distillation is worth it:** once a domain has *stable, abundant, verifier-labeled* data and token-space memory/skills have visibly plateaued for that domain (retrieval can't compress the pattern further). It buys latency (shorter prompts, no skill-injection overhead) and capability the context window can't hold. Until then, token-space memory/skills give most of the gain at near-zero risk — which is the consensus framing: distill only after a distilled subset of domain data justifies the compute. ([PMC12634706](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12634706/))\n\n---\n\n## Candidate (ii): Outcome-learned routing\n\n### This is the closest match to what Yogi already has\nYour Think/NoThink navigator + qwen3's native `enable_thinking` / `/think` / `/no_think` toggle is *exactly* the control surface these papers route over. Qwen3 is a hybrid model where mode is a per-turn parameter — no extra model needed to act on a routing decision. ([Qwen3 hybrid thinking](https://debuggercafe.com/qwen3-unified-models-for-thinking-and-non-thinking/), [Qwen3-32B card](https://huggingface.co/Qwen/Qwen3-32B))\n\n### ThinkSwitcher — the template to copy\nThis is the load-bearing finding. ThinkSwitcher routes a *single* hybrid reasoning model between short and long CoT using recorded outcomes — your exact problem:\n- **Signal = empirical pass rates per mode.** For each training query it samples k=8 responses under both short and long CoT, computes pass rate P_m(q) ∈ [0,1] per mode. That is precisely the recorded pass/fail-per-task-class signal you proposed.\n- **Router = a tiny MLP** (5 linear layers, dims [1024,768,512,256,2]) over the model's prompt embedding; **~10M FLOPs/query vs ~100T for decoding** — negligible, and crucially *not an LLM call*.\n- **Decision rule**: pick long CoT when predicted advantage (y_long − y_short) exceeds threshold τ; τ is a tunable accuracy/cost knob.\n- **Results (7B):** ~29% token reduction at ~2% accuracy drop vs long-only; on GSM8K, **30% token savings at <1% accuracy loss**. **Smaller models gain disproportionately** — the 1.5B model saved >30% tokens while holding accuracy, because weak models over-elaborate. qwen3:8b is squarely in the \"benefits a lot\" zone. ([ThinkSwitcher arXiv 2505.14183](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.14183v1), [abs](https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.14183))\n\n### Bandit framing (if you want online adaptation rather than a trained regressor)\n- The bandit literature treats mode/model selection as a contextual bandit over a prompt embedding, learning from the chosen action's outcome only (\"only the outcome of the chosen model is observed\") — exactly bandit feedback. **BaRP** (policy-gradient contextual bandit) reports +3.8% in-distribution over the best single model and **~50% cost reduction vs an offline router while scoring higher**; a single preference-weighted policy spans the accuracy/cost frontier at inference time via a cost weight. ([BaRP arXiv 2510.07429](https://arxiv.org/html/2510.07429v1))\n- Classic algorithms in this space: **LinUCB, Thompson sampling, ε-greedy**. MetaLLM/PILOT use LinUCB over query embeddings with an accuracy-minus-cost reward; PILOT specifically seeds LinUCB with offline preference data to handle cold-start. ([MetaLLM/PILOT survey context, arXiv 2506.17670](https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.17670), [routing survey arXiv 2603.04445](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.04445))\n\n### How much it helps vs a good heuristic, and cold-start\n- Gains over a *good* heuristic are modest-but-real on accuracy (low single digits) and larger on cost/tokens (20-50% range across ThinkSwitcher/BaRP). The win for Yogi is mostly **cost-aware**: same accuracy, fewer thinking tokens, lower latency — which directly feeds your metabolism/budget machinery.\n- **Cold-start is the one genuine concern**, and it's solved cheaply: (a) ε-greedy / Thompson exploration, (b) warm-start LinUCB priors from offline logs (PILOT), or (c) ThinkSwitcher's approach — fall back to the existing heuristic until a task-class has enough recorded outcomes, then switch to learned. You already produce the outcomes (the falsification/being-bench harness), so the training signal is free. ([ThinkSwitcher](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.14183v1), [PILOT/MetaLLM survey](https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.17670))\n- 2024-2026 work specifically on *learned reasoning-effort routing* is now a cluster: ThinkSwitcher, RouteLLM, SelfBudgeter, ARES (adaptive reasoning effort for agents), RTR, and survey coverage in arXiv 2511.10788 — the field has converged on \"route effort by predicted difficulty.\" ([survey arXiv 2511.10788](https://arxiv.org/html/2511.10788v2), [ARES arXiv 2603.07915](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.07915))\n\n---\n\n## Recommendation: build outcome-learned routing next\n\n**Why it beats distillation as the next layer:**\n1. **Constraint fit.** The router is an MLP / linear bandit doing ~10M FLOPs — no model load, no second resident model, no concurrent-inference problem. It can run inside `cargo test --all` and the hooks **without ever calling Ollama**, satisfying the HARD RULE. Distillation can't — training is heavy inference and must be foreground-gated.\n2. **Lower risk, no regression surface.** Routing never degrades the base model's weights; worst case it falls back to the heuristic. Distillation risks catastrophic forgetting and tiny-data overfit that you'd have to build eval gates to catch.\n3. **It compounds what you already certified.** It upgrades the Think/NoThink navigator from heuristic to outcome-learned, and it learns *which skill to load* by the same recorded pass/fail signal — directly leveraging the verifier-fed skills and memory you already have. The training data (per-task-class pass/fail) is already produced by being-bench.\n4. **Research-validated, hardware-agnostic gains.** 20-30% token/latency savings at ≤2% accuracy cost, with weak models (your 8B/qwen3) gaining the most.\n5. **It earns distillation's keep.** Routing's recorded pass-rate-per-task-class is *exactly the diagnostic* that tells you when a domain has plateaued in token-space — i.e. when distillation (M3) finally becomes worth the risk. So routing is the right precursor.\n\n### Minimal first implementation sketch\n- **Surface to route**: the existing Think/NoThink toggle (map to qwen3 `enable_thinking` / `/no_think`) plus skill-load on/off. Start with the binary Think/NoThink decision only; add skill selection in a second pass.\n- **Context features**: reuse the shared `nomic-embed-text` prompt embedding you already compute for memory retrieval — zero extra inference cost. Optionally append cheap task-class tags.\n- **Learner**: start with **LinUCB or Thompson over per-task-class buckets** (simpler to reason about and ship than an MLP, and gives principled exploration for cold-start). Reward = `correct ? 1 : 0` minus a tunable `λ · normalized_thinking_tokens` (or microdollar cost) — wiring routing into the metabolism/budget ledger you built in M1.\n- **Cold-start**: until a task-class has N (e.g. 20-30) recorded outcomes, use the current heuristic; once past N, use the learned arm with ε-greedy/Thompson exploration. (PILOT-style: seed priors from existing being-bench logs if available.)\n- **Training/update**: fully CPU, no model inference → runs in the automated loop and hooks legally. Update the bandit from being-bench's recorded pass/fail per turn.\n- **Acceptance test (M-style)**: on a held-out task set, learned router matches always-Think accuracy within ~2% while cutting thinking tokens ≥20% vs always-Think and beating the static heuristic on the accuracy-per-token frontier. (ThinkSwitcher's reported envelope is your target.)\n- **Knob**: expose τ / cost-weight λ so a human can slide the accuracy↔cost frontier without retraining — matching the BaRP single-policy-many-tradeoffs design.\n\n---\n\n## Sources\n- [InsiderLLM — Fine-Tuning on Mac: LoRA & QLoRA with MLX](https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-mac-lora-mlx/)\n- [Markaicode — Run and Fine-Tune LLMs on Mac with MLX-LM](https://markaicode.com/run-fine-tune-llms-mac-mlx-lm/)\n- [mlx-tune (GitHub)](https://github.com/ARahim3/mlx-tune)\n- [Lyceum — LoRA vs Full Fine-Tuning Memory Cost / VRAM math](https://lyceum.technology/magazine/lora-vs-full-fine-tuning-memory-cost/)\n- [Modal — How much VRAM for fine-tuning](https://modal.com/blog/how-much-vram-need-fine-tuning)\n- [MLX Unified Memory docs](https://ml-explore.github.io/mlx/build/html/usage/unified_memory.html)\n- [MLX issue #3078 — concurrent inference of independent models](https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx/issues/3078)\n- [Catastrophic forgetting regularization — arXiv 2501.13669](https://arxiv.org/html/2501.13669v2)\n- [KD/dataset distillation survey — PMC12634706](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12634706/)\n- [Survey on KD of LLMs — arXiv 2402.13116](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2402.13116)\n- [ThinkSwitcher: When to Think Hard, When to Think Fast — arXiv 2505.14183](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.14183v1) ([abs](https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.14183))\n- [BaRP — Learning to Route LLMs from Bandit Feedback — arXiv 2510.07429](https://arxiv.org/html/2510.07429v1)\n- [Online Multi-LLM Selection via Contextual Bandits (LinUCB/MetaLLM/PILOT) — arXiv 2506.17670](https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.17670)\n- [Dynamic Model Routing & Cascading survey — arXiv 2603.04445](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.04445)\n- [From Efficiency to Adaptivity (adaptive reasoning survey) — arXiv 2511.10788](https://arxiv.org/html/2511.10788v2)\n- [ARES: Adaptive Reasoning Effort Selection — arXiv 2603.07915](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.07915)\n- [Qwen3 hybrid thinking / enable_thinking](https://debuggercafe.com/qwen3-unified-models-for-thinking-and-non-thinking/), [Qwen3-32B model card](https://huggingface.co/Qwen/Qwen3-32B)"}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2874,"cache_read_input_tokens":25077,"output_tokens":5766,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2874},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":5766,"cache_read_input_tokens":25077,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2874,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2874,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFxCdYAjujiVGWKRdfS9","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"d966e510-87eb-4bbd-b3d2-f97d26c8da9c","timestamp":"2026-06-21T06:45:32.666Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
